CoVs are a subfamily of large, enveloped viruses that contain a unique strand of sensitive RNA.
These viruses can be divided into four classes alpha, beta, gamma and delta, with identified alpha and beta variants of CoVs that can infect humans.
Spinal envelope glycoprotein (S) attaches to the host cell angiotensin and is converted to ACE2 (ACE2) and DPP4 (DPP4) respectively for SARS-CoV and MERS-CoV, and then membrane fusion occurs.
The RNA genome of the virus is released in the cytoplasm; after the viral genome is replicated, the RNA genome with enveloped glycoproteins and nucleocapsid proteins forms vesicle-containing sacs which then attach to the plasma membrane to release the virus.
