These regions accounted for 80% of the country's GDP and 90% of its exports.
Hong Kong raised the level of infectious disease control to the highest level and declared a state of emergency, closed schools until March and canceled New Year's celebrations.
Visitors to retail stores in Europe and Latin America fell by 40%.
Retail stores in North America and the Middle East saw 60-50% of reviews.
The outbreak also led to a 43-33% drop in pedestrian traffic to shopping malls in March compared to February.
According to estimates by the United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America, the recession created by the pandemic could push between 14 and 22 million people in Latin America into extreme poverty, a situation that would not have been possible without the pandemic.
